Port to Linux 6.18 investigation: dpa_app never raises libfmc's own log
level above the default NONE, so libfmc's fmc_log_write() calls at LOG_ERR
(e.g. "Invocation of FM_PCD_KgSchemeSet for %s failed" in fmc_exec.c) are
silently dropped at boot. All we get today is dpa_app's own generic
"unable to execute the FMC Model", with no indication of which scheme(s)
actually failed inside libfmc.

Raise the log level to LOG_ERR at the top of dpa_init(), before
fmc_compile()/fmc_execute() run, so libfmc's own error detail reaches
stderr (captured by the dpa_app_wrapper script under
ASK_DPA_APP_DEBUG=1). This is diagnostic-only: it does not change any
FMan/PCD programming behavior, just what gets logged on failure.

--- a/dpa_app-4.03.0/dpa.c
+++ b/dpa_app-4.03.0/dpa.c
@@ -756,6 +756,11 @@
 	char devname[64];
 	int retval;

+	/* Surface libfmc's own per-call error detail (e.g. which PCD
+	 * scheme/port failed), which is otherwise dropped at the default
+	 * log level of NONE. */
+	fmc_log(LOG_ERR);
+
 	//open cdx control device
         sprintf(devname, "/dev/%s", CDX_CTRL_CDEVNAME);
         cdx_dev_handle = open(devname, O_RDWR);
